  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I look good in pictures?",
  "response": "Looking good in pictures is all about understanding your angles, lighting, and posture. Here are some tips to help you shine in photos:\n\n### 1. **Perfect Your Posture**\n   - Stand or sit up straight to look confident and elongates your body.\n   - Push your shoulders slightly back and down to avoid a hunched look.\n   - Angle your body slightly (instead of standing straight on) for a more flattering silhouette.\n\n### 2. **Find Your Best Angle**\n   - Experiment with different angles in the mirror to find your most flattering side.\n   - Tilt your head slightly to one side rather than being completely straight.\n   - Avoid holding the camera too low\u2014eye level or slightly above is usually the most flattering.\n\n### 3. **Master Your Expression**\n   - Smile naturally by thinking of something that makes you genuinely happy.\n   - Practice a relaxed, slight smile or a neutral expression if you don\u2019t want to smile.\n   - Avoid a forced or overly wide smile, which can look unnatural.\n\n### 4. **Work with Lighting**\n   - Natural light is your best friend\u2014position yourself facing a window or outdoors.\n   - Avoid harsh overhead lighting or direct sunlight, which can cast shadows.\n   - Soft, diffused lighting is the most flattering for skin tones.\n\n### 5. **Focus on the Eyes**\n   - Look slightly above the camera lens to avoid a dull gaze.\n   - If the photo is candid, focus on something you\u2019re genuinely interested in to make your expression authentic.\n   - Use eye drops to reduce redness and get a bright-eyed look.\n\n### 6. **Experiment with Poses**\n   - Shift your weight to one leg to create a more dynamic pose.\n   - Place your hands naturally\u2014on your hip, in your pocket, or lightly touching your face.\n   - Avoid stiff, straight-on poses; add movement or a slight lean.\n\n### 7. **Wear Flattering Outfits**\n   - Choose colors and styles that complement your skin tone and body shape.\n   - Avoid overly busy patterns or logos that distract from your face.\n   - Solid colors or subtle patterns work well for photos.\n\n### 8. **Groom and Prep**\n   - Ensure your hair is styled and neat, and your skin looks fresh.\n   - Use a little makeup or grooming products to enhance your features (e.g., concealer, mascara, lip balm).\n   - Shine some powder to reduce shine on your face.\n\n### 9. **Practice Relaxation**\n   - Take a deep breath and relax your face and body before the photo.\n   - Avoid tensing up or overthinking\u2014confidence makes a huge difference.\n\n### 10. **Edit Thoughtfully**\n   - Use photo editing apps to make subtle adjustments, like brightness, contrast, or color balance.\n   - Avoid over-editing, which can make your photo look unnatural.\n\n### 11. **Be Yourself**\n   - Authenticity always looks better than trying too hard. Embrace your natural beauty and personality.\n\nWith these tips and a little practice, you'll be camera-ready in no time!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
